The Red Wine Quality data set contains information about over 1,500 red wines with 11 variables that describe the chemical characteristics of wine. The data set provides a rating of the quality of each wine, with 0 being the lowest quality and 10 being the greatest quality.

Some questions that would be relevant to this dataset are what chemical characteristics do quality wines share, do wines with higher alcohol content receive better ratings, do sweeter wines receive better ratings, what level of acidity is associated with higher quality wines.

Univariate Plots Section

The histogram for fixed acidity is right skewed. Most of the observations fall in the 7-8 range.

I was hoping to find a different distribution of fixed acidity for higher quality wines, but the distributions for all the wine qualities seem similar with most observations falling in the 6 to 11 range.

The distribution for volatile.acidity is more disperse, but still, most of the observations fall in the lower half of the values, between .3 and .7 with some outliers having values around 1.6.

Volatile acidity is the amount of acetic acid in wine which according to the text file that comes with the data set, at too high levels might give an unpleasant taste to the wine. We can notice that higher quality wines do have a slighltly smaller value for volatile acidity in comparison to the lesser quality wines.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The data set is made of 1599 observations of red wines with 11 variables that describe their chemical properties.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature of interest in the dataset is the quality ranking for each wine. It might be really interesting to find out what factors affect the quality of wine the most.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your
investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

I think alcohol content, volatile acidity, citric acid, chlorides and sulphates might be the chemical properties that could have the most weight when determining the quality of wine.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I created the variable alcohol_ranking, using the quantiles of the alcohol sample, I classified each wine either as low, medium low, medium high, or high. Finally, I converted that variable into a factor because that will be really useful when performing multiple variable analysis.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?
Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Most distributions were right skewed. Just density, pH and quality followed a normal distribution. I didn’t feel the need to change the form of the data, the only modification done was calculating mean, median and quantiles of certain features in order to understand the distributions better.

Bivariate Plots Section

Low quality wines have a small alcohol content mean, with quality #3 having a value around 10, quality 4 moving upwards a little bit, and quality 5 going back down under quality #3, but after that, there is a consistent linear increment in the alcohol content mean as the quality improves, reaching the peak of the distribution at the highest quality.

This time we have an inverted trend where volatile acidity decreases as the quality improves. We can notice that high quality wines have a much smaller distribution, with most observations being around the value of .4 for volatile acidity, which is not the case for other wine qualities that have a more spread out distribution.

For citric acid, there is a clear trend that shows how citric acid increases as the quality of wine improves.

It doesn’t seem that residual sugar is likely to have an impact on quality.

It does seem that higher quality wines usually have a smaller value for chlorides in comparison to lower quality wines, but the differnce is small.

There seems to be a trend where as the wine quality improves, the wine has a higher level of sulphates.

The relationship between fixed acidity and volatile acidity is not very clear. It seems that most observations have a fixed and volatile acidity in the lower half of the range.

Most wines have a residual sugar level that is less than 4, even across the different levels of fixed acidity. I thought that maybe acidity could be used to balance the sweetness of a wine, so I was hoping to find that wines with a higher level of fixed acidity would be less sweet. This chart doesn’t tell that narrative.

There seems to be a really small trend when chlorides increase so does the density of wine.

I have heard before that really sweet wines usually have more alcohol. This graph discredits that belief. Most wines, no matter how much alcohol they have, are in the low end of the spectrum regarding residual sugar. Among those outliers with a lot of residual sugar, most of them fall in the low alcohol content category.

This graph clearly shows how higher quality wines have a higher alcohol content, not only a higher mean or median, but the entire distribution is above the values that lower quality wines have.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset?

Some of the relationships I observed were about quality against different features: alcohol, volatile acidity, chlorides, sulphates and citric acid. Even though most of the scatterplots showed a trend that links these various features with quality, the correlations were non-significant and the trends too weak, with the exception of alcohol and quality.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features
(not the main feature(s) of interest)?

Yes, I had the idea that really sweet wines had a higher alcohol content. The scatterplot not only debunked this myth, since most wines are not that sweet regardless of their alcohol content, but out of those wines that are sweet, they usually have a low alcohol content.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship I found is between alcohol and quality. The correlation test came out with a result of 0.476 which is a moderate but significant correlation, and when comparing the alcohol content means across quality, the high quality wines have a signficant higher alcohol content than low quality wines.

Multivariate Plots Section

Here we have a graph for each quality ranking that describes the relationship between alcohol and volatile.acidity. Low quality wines have a low alcohol content and a relatively high volatile acidity. On the other hand, high quality wines have a higher alcohol content and a lower volatile acidity.

This graph shows the relation of alcohol and citric acid for each quality level. High quality wines have a higher alcohol content with medium levels of citric acid.

Nothing particular stands out.

This graph confirms that the sweetest wines have the lowest alcohol content and also that high quality wines tend to have low levels for residual sugar.

Wines with a low alcohol ranking (green dot) are the ones that have higher values for chlorides.

There is a clear trend that establishes a relationship between citric acid and volatile acidity. When levels of citric acid are high, volatile acidity tends to be low, this is specially true in high quality wines. The opposite is also true, when volatile acidity is high, citric acid tends to be low, this happens more often with lower quality wines.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the
investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest?

For this section, I already had a clear idea that alcohol content was the most important feature in determining the quality of wine. So I focused my attention on describing the relationship of alcohol with other features of the dataset. High quality wines (which have high alcohol content), have low levels for volatile acidity and medium levels for citric acid. Another interesting relationship is that of high quality wines and residual sugar, that shows that high quality wines have a low content of residual sugar, thus describing a high quality wine that is high in alcohol content and dry regarding its residual sugar.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

Yes, the most interesting being the relationship between chlorides, alcohol content and quality. It turns out that levels of chlorides remain steady across the dataset with the exception of low alcohol wines, that have a clear spike in their levels of chlorides, which might suggest a relation between chlorides and alcohol content. Another relation that derives from the previous one is that this low alcohol - high chlorides wines appear exclusevily in the levels of quality 5 and 6.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

Description One

This graph shows the strongest relationship I found in the dataset: Alcohol and Quality. If we follow the means of each quality distribution, we can see a clear trend that starts at quality level 5, where the alcohol content increases as the quality improves. As a result, wines with a quality of 6 have a higher alcohol content than wines with a quality of 5, wines with a quality of 7 have even higher alcohol content, and wines with a quality of 8 have the highest alcohol content of the sample. It is also clear that for the highest quality wines with a quality ranking #8, the bulk of the distribution (interquantile range) has a higher alcohol content than that of the entire distribution of wines with quality ranking #3.

Plot Two

Description Two

I like this plot because it weakens the myth that sweet wines have a high alcohol content. Most wines, regardless of their quality, have a residual sugar level of 4g/l, that categorizes them as dry. This is specially true with high quality wines with a ranking of 8, since most of the distribution is below this parameter. It is also clear that quality ranking #7 and #5 have the highest number of observations in the medium-dry range which covers from 4g/l up to 12g/l. We can only observe a couple of wines with a quality of 8 in this category. Finally, in the sweetest wines in this plot, above 12g/l which is considered a medium sweetness, we don’t have any observations of quality #8 wines.

Plot Three

Description Three

This graph shows the relationship between volatile acidity and citric acid by comparing the different alcohol rankings across the different quality rankings. For low quality wines such as #3, is has become clear that they have a lower alcohol content since there are no observations of wines with a high alcohol content in that quality ranking. Furthermore, low quality wines seem to have a higher value for volatile acidity and lower values for citric acid. When comparing quality rankings #3 against #8, this becomes obvious: While quality ranking #3 has most of their observations with a value above .8 for volatile acidity, quality ranking #8 has most of its observations with a value below .6 for volatile acidity; while quality ranking #3 has most of its observations with a value below .25 for citric acid, quality ranking #8 has most of its observations with a value above .25 for citric acid. All quality rankings follow the trend that when volatile acidity is high, citric acid is low; and when volatile acidity is low, citric acid is high.

Reflection

Here I list some of the key insights found through this exploration.

The sample follows a normal distribution for quality, with most wines having a quality of 5 or 6. One surprising of the dataset is that there wasn’t a single observation below 3 or above a quality of 8.

Alcohol content proved to be one of the most important features when determining if a wine is high quality. According to the sample, most high quality wine have a high alcohol content while most of the low quality wines have also a low alcohol content.

One interesting relationship is that between alcohol content and residual sugar. Some people think that the sweeter the wine the more alcohol it has. It turns out this is not true, but opposite is. Most of the wines with high quality have lower levels of residual sugar, and from those wines that have a high level of residual sugar, they are usually pretty low in alcohol.

It also was really interesting to observe how the relation between different variables changed in each quality category. For example, volatile acidity and citric acid experience a constant trend throughout the data set where if volatile acidity increases, citric acid decreases and also the opposite. This became more obvious with high quality wines that have a much lower level of volatile acidity, thus, higher levels of citric acid.

One of the main struggles is quantity of variables that affect the quality of wine. Since there are so many, any subtle difference could change the quality of the wine dramatically, so it was really difficult to establish trends among the entire sample.

In the future it could be really interesting to add the type of red wine that is being graded, since that could change the rating dramatically since one is looking for different characteristics when tasting a cabernet sauvignon to a zinfandel for example. Having some wines with a quality of 9 or 10 could also be really interesting and perhaps help establish stronger trends in the data.
